The '''Concerned Businessmen's Association of America''' (CBAA), founded in 1983, is a [[Scientology]]-related movement directed at promoting moral education and "enhanced well-being". The organization uses [[L. Ron Hubbard]]'s ''[[The Way to Happiness]]'' booklet as part of their Set A Good Example (SAGE) program, which holds children's anti-drug contests, and awards grants to participating schools.<ref>{{cite web | first = Robert W. | last = Welkos |author2=Sappell, Joel | title = Church Seeks Influence in Schools, Business, Science | url = http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-scientology062790,0,884315,full.story | work = | publisher = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = 1990-06-27 | accessdate = 2007-10-30 }}</ref> ''The Way to Happiness'' presents Scientology's religious concepts in a secular framework.<ref>{{cite news|title=Scientology In The Schools|url=http://www.newsweek.com/scientology-schools-194002|accessdate=2 December 2013|newspaper=Newsweek|date=13 June 1993}}</ref> The CBAA licenses the trademarks of the [[Association for Better Living and Education]] (ABLE). Their office is located in [[Reno, Nevada]].
==Media mention== In 1988, [[St. Petersburg Times]] listed them as "A Glendale, Calif.-based group of Scientologists that promotes drug-free living through its Way to Happiness book and like-named campaign, targeted to school-age children."<ref>{{cite web |url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sptimes/access/51440809.html?dids=51440809:51440809&FMT=FT&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Dec+22%2C+1988&author=STEPHEN+KOFF&pub=St.+Petersburg+Times&edition=&startpage=6.A&desc=Dozens+of+groups+operate+under+auspices+of+Church+of+Scientology&pf=1 |title = Dozens of groups operate under auspices of Church of Scientology |accessdate = 2007-08-04 |last = Koff |first = Stephen |date = 1988-12-22 |work = [[St. Petersburg Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | first = Stephen | last = Koff | title = Changing strategy: Scientology now steps right up to controversy | url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sptimes/access/51441692.html?FMT=FT | work = | publisher = [[St. Petersburg Times]] | date = 1988-12-23 | accessdate = 2007-12-13 }}</ref>
In 1991, [[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]] listed the CBAA as a [[Church of Scientology]]-linked group that "holds antidrug contests and awards $5,000 grants to schools as a way to recruit students and curry favor with education officials."<ref name="Behar">{{cite news | first = Richard | last = Behar | url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,972865-6,00.html | title = The Thriving Cult of Greed and Power | work = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date = 1991-05-06 | accessdate= 2007-02-06}}</ref>
In 1998, the [[Boston Herald]] listed them on an organization chart under "Groups that teach Hubbard’s management techniques".<ref>{{cite web | first = Jeff | last = Walsh | title = A broader look at the organization| work = Inside the Church of Scientology | publisher = [[Boston Herald]] | date = 1998-03-01 }}</ref>
