{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}} {{Infobox_ancient_site | name = Kolvi Caves | native_name = Kolvi Caves | alternate_name = | image = Kolvi caves.jpg | imagealttext = Kolvi caves. | caption = Kolvi caves. | map_type = India |relief=yes | map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|24.0118137|75.8480568|display=inline, title}} | location = | region = | type = Buddhist caves | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | height = | builder = | material = | built = | abandoned = | epochs = | cultures = | dependency_of = | occupants = | event = | excavations = | archaeologists = | condition = | ownership = | public_access = | website = | notes = }} {{BuddhasHolySites}} '''Kolvi Caves''' or Kholve caves are located at Kolvi village in the state of [[Rajasthan]], [[India]]. They are carved out in [[laterite]] rock hill. This [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] site has [[stupa]]s, [[chaitya]]s containing figures of [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]]. An architectural style shows dominance of [[Hinayana]] sect in this region. The caves has statues of Buddha in the [[meditation]] and standing position.<ref name="BUDDHIST CAVES,">{{cite web|last=Jaipur Circle, ASI|title=BUDDHIST CAVES, PILLARS AND LDOLS|url=http://asijaipurcircle.nic.in/Kolvi-Buddhist%20Caves,Pillars&Idols.html#des|publisher=Archaeological Survey of India|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> The stupas and colossal statues of Buddha are archaeologically significant.<ref name="A new dot">{{cite news|title=A new dot on the tourism map|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/story-print/159453|accessdate=30 November 2013|newspaper=The Financial Express|date=20 November 2005}}</ref> Around Kolva village similar caves have been discovered which proves existence of prosperous Buddhist civilization in the region.<ref>{{cite web|title=Buddhist Caves, Kolvi|url=http://jhalawar.nic.in/kolvi.htm|publisher=Jhalawar District, Government of Rajasthan|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>
==The caves== The caves are in state of natural weathering resulting complete damage on northern and eastern side, but their remains are important in the architecture.<ref name="BUDDHIST CAVES," /> The group has 50 caves in which many caves have lost their figure faces due to decaying. Currently caves are not occupied.<ref name=Kumar>{{cite news|last=Kumar|first=Arjun|title=Rajasthan's best kept secret: 3 Buddhist cave complexes|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-04-22/news/31379426_1_caves-monks-hill|accessdate=30 November 2013|newspaper=The Ecomomic Times|date=22 April 2012}}</ref> Few caves have open or pillered verandah.<ref name=Hadoti>{{cite web|last=Hadoti Tourism Development Society|title=Jhalawar|url=http://www.bundikota.com/jhalawar.htm|publisher=Hadoti Tourism Development Society|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>
