{{Distinguish|Ziziphus jujube}} {{speciesbox |image = Ziziphus-areva-israel.jpg |genus = Ziziphus |species = spina-christi |authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|L.]])[[René Louiche Desfontaines|Desf.]] |synonyms = {{Plainlist | style = margin-left: 1em; text-indent: -1em; | *''Rhamnus spina-christi'' <small>L.</small> }} |synonyms_ref = <ref>{{citation |url=http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl1.1/record/tro-27501041 |title=The Plant List: A Working List of All Plant Species |accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref> }}
'''''Ziziphus spina-christi''''', known as the '''Christ's thorn jujube''', is an evergreen tree or plant native to northern and tropical [[Africa]], [[Southern Asia|Southern]] and [[Western Asia]]. It is native to the regions [[Levant]], [[East Africa]] and some tropical countries.<ref>http://www.worldagroforestry.org/treedb/AFTPDFS/Zizyphus_spina-christi.PDF</ref>
==Ecology== In the Levant, it grows in valleys up to an elevation of 500&nbsp;m.<ref>Zohary M. Flora Palaestina. II. Jerusalem: The Israel Academy of Science and Humanities; 1972. pp. 307–308 cited in {{citation|title=The ethnobotany of Christ's Thorn Jujube (Ziziphus spina-christi) in Israel|author1=Amots Dafni |author2=Shay Levy |author3=Efraim Lev |last-author-amp=yes |pmc=1277088 | pmid=16270941|doi=10.1186/1746-4269-1-8 |volume=1 |year=2005 |journal=J Ethnobiol Ethnomed |pages=8}}</ref> The ripe fruits are edible.<ref>[http://www.beesfordevelopment.org/info/info/flora/christs-thorn-ziziphus-sp.shtml ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100424201940/http://www.beesfordevelopment.org/info/info/flora/christs-thorn-ziziphus-sp.shtml |date=April 24, 2010 }}</ref> The seed, contained in a small, oblong wooden pit, is opened and eaten by local fauna, such as the [[rock hyrax]].
==Cultural and religious references== In the Levant, a hundred years ago, it was called ''[[Sidrat al-Muntaha|sidr]]'' (associated with the [[Sidrat al-Muntaha|Lote-trees]] of the [[Quran]]) and was common in the [[Jordan Valley (Middle East)|Jordan Valley]] and around [[Jerusalem]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Illustrated Bible Dictionary and Treasury of Biblical History, Biography, Geography, Doctrine, and Literature: With Numerous Illustrations and Important Chronological Tables and Maps. |author=[[Matthew George Easton|Easton, M.G., M.A., D.D.]] |year=1893 |location=London, Edinburgh and New York |publisher=T. Nelson and Sons |page=688 |url= |quote=«It overruns a great part of the Jordan valley.» p.174. Easton argues that the spina-christi is too brittle to be bent into a crown. He suggests another local plant which he says is called «nabk». |accessdate= }}</ref> There were some folklore traditions that said the trees were protected by benevolent spirits or dead saints ([[Wali|''weli'']]). By some traditions, it was the tree from which Jesus' [[crown of thorns]] was made.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flowersinisrael.com/Ziziphusspina-christi_page.htm |title=Ziziphus spina-christi |publisher=Flowersinisrael.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-09}}</ref> [[Matthew George Easton|Easton]] argues that the spina-christi is too brittle to be bent into a crown, and suggests another local plant which he says is called "[[Ziziphus lotus|nabk]]."<ref>[[Matthew George Easton|Easton, M.G., M.A., D.D.]] (1893) 'Illustrated Bible Dictionary and Treasury of Biblical History, Biography, Geography, Doctrine, and Literature With Numerous Illustrations and Important Chronological Tables and Maps.'' T. Nelson and Sons, London, Edinburgh and New York. p.174</ref>
The oldest known Ziziphus is located south of Jerusalem, in Ayn Husb, Palestine. It estimated to be about 2000 years old. It is believed locally to be the very tree from which Jesus' crown of thorns was made.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oldest trees in Israel|url=https://he.wikipedia.org/wiki/%D7%A2%D7%A6%D7%99%D7%9D_%D7%A2%D7%AA%D7%99%D7%A7%D7%99%D7%9D_%D7%91%D7%90%D7%A8%D7%A5_%D7%99%D7%A9%D7%A8%D7%90%D7%9C}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=February 2018}}
